problem link: https://leetcode.com/problems/combination-sum/description/
Intuition
Approach: Backtracking (Include/Exclude at each index)
for each candidate at index i , we have two choices

skip it - move to i + 1 without adding it to current combination
take it add it to current combination and stay at index i , since we are allowed to reuse the same element.
we recurse until either the running total equals target (valid combination found) or we run out of candidates i == n. the total + candiddates[i] <= target checks branches early so we dont recurse into paths that never succeed , thats what keep this efficient rather than blowing up.

since diary is mutable list being shared across recursive calls , we append before recursing and pop after backtracking so it's correctly reset when we try another branches.

Complexity
Time complexity:
O(2^t*k) where T is the target value and k is the average length of a combination. The recursion explores many possible combinations, and insertion into the set requires comparing vectors.

Space complexity:
O(M × k)

where M is the number of unique combinations stored in the set and k is the average size of each combination. Additionally, the recursion stack can grow up to O(T) in the worst case.

Code
class Solution:
    def combinationSum(self, candidates: List[int], target: int) -> List[List[int]]:
        diary = []
        result = []
        n = len(candidates)
        def fun(i, total):
            if i == n:
                if total == target:
                    result.append(diary.copy())
                return
            #choice 1 not taking
            fun(i+1,total)
            #choice2 taking it
            if candidates[i] + total <= target:
                diary.append(candidates[i])
                fun(i , total + candidates[i])
                diary.pop()
            
            return
        fun(0,0)
        return result
